"x0": 25.655, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 38.735, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "Left", "x0": 39.614, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 43.805, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "pleural", "x0": 44.692, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 51.876, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "collection", "x0": 52.767, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 62.298, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "is", "x0": 63.182, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 64.762, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "also", "x0": 65.635, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 69.625, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "demonstrated", "x0": 70.516, "y0": 40.546, "x1": 84.358, "y1": 42.213}, {"t": "(black", "x0": 13.509, "y0": 42.612, "x1": 19.794, "y1": 44.28}, {"t": "arrow).", "x0": 20.384, "y0": 42.612, "x1": 27.839, "y1": 44.28}], "images": [{"x0": 67.75, "y0": 4.86, "x1": 81.9, "y1": 7.04}, {"x0": 7.3, "y0": 4.92, "x1": 39.83, "y1": 7.11}, {"x0": 45.61, "y0": 0.89, "x1": 53.74, "y1": 6.95}, {"x0": 61.37, "y0": 2.04, "x1": 68.04, "y1": 6.76}, {"x0": 14.6, "y0": 9.44, "x1": 85.58, "y1": 33.58}, {"x0": 25.69, "y0": 76.0, "x1": 74.57, "y1": 92.17}], "full_text": "Radiology\nContrast enhanced chest CT axial (A) and coronal (B) planes in a\npatient with penetrating injury. There is rupture of the lateral wall of\nthe left ventricle (white arrow) with contrast extravasation and\ntamponade (arrowhead). Left pleural collection is also demonstrated\n(black arrow).\nNon Cardiovascular Trauma\n1. Pulmonary parenchymal injury: The most common types of lung parenchymal\ninjury are: contusions, lacerations, and hematomas, each having characteristic\nimaging appearances.\n2. Pleural: pneumothorax and hemothorax\n3. Airway injury\n4. Oesophageal perforation\nPulmonary contusions\n• The most common type of pulmonary parenchymal injury, occurring in up to 75%\nof blunt chest trauma cases\n• The characteristic radiologic feature of lung contusions on chest radiographs is\nthat of focal patchy or diffuse non-segmental hazy airspace opacities. Opacities\nmay become consolidative when bleeding is more extensive, in which case air\nbronchograms may be evident when regional airways are clear.\n73"}